reviewText:
MARTY, starring Ernest Borgnine, concerns a turning point in the life of a thirty something gentleman.  The fact-pattern in MARTY is representative of certain challenges, or situations, that confront thousands, or perhaps millions, of American men.  Hence, this film could be viewed as being a documentary of one a typical life pathway for American men.  In fact, a reasonable alternate title for this movie would be, "A Week in the Life of Mister Generic Everyman."  Perhaps, because this films restrains from any attempt to be comedic, refrains from attempts to be unusual, refrains from including any characters with a debilitation or with an unusual talent or skill, and refrains from any sense of adventure or mystery, the film manages to avoid making any false steps.  Does this make a great movie?  In other words, if the scriptwriter and director manage to assemble a cinematic work that refrains from making any false steps during the course of 90 minutes, does this along cause the movie to be a great movie?  I don't know, perhaps, perhaps not.

The particular life pathway that is documented by MARTY is for an American man with the following qualities:

(1) Has career ambitions but, for the moment, is still operating at entry level;
(2) Has ambitions to be a "conventional" family man but, while approaching his mid thirties, has yet to meet a woman who will accept him;
(3) Occupies a transition point where his parents (in this movie, his mother) considers ethnic background to be important, but where the protagonist (Mr. Borgnine) does not consider ethnic background to be relevant in a potential marriage partner;
(4) Has friends and acquaintances who are, for the most part, unskilled, unmotivated, and who occupy the gutter of society;
(5) Has relatives who are drama queens (argumentative);
(6) Is not physically attractive but, more importantly, dwells occasionally on the fact that he is not physically attractive.

Thus, the above list represents certain qualities that pertain to a chunk of the American populace. The movie is more like a case history in a psychology textbook, or in a sociology textbook, than a typical drama. There is little or nothing in this movie to make it stand out from the millions of lives that are played out by men in their mid-thirties, in the United States of America.  But what makes this film a successful one, is that the sterotypical story is skillfully presented.

MARTY concerns a 35 year old butcher (Mr. Borgnine) who is not adept with women. But he has the admirable quality of never giving up, and eventually, at the town dance hall, he eventually meets the woman of his life.  The woman happens to be a high school chemistry teacher, trained at New York Univesity . . . but her hangup is that she has no personality.  (This was obviously the intention of the scriptwriter and the director -- that the woman should be devoid of any personality.)  And so, the spark of love is ignited by the fact that Mr. Borgnine has had no luck in his quest for a domestic, married life (because of his lack of social skills), and by the fact that the woman has had no luck, apparently for the same reasons.  The two share this quality.  They also share the quality of being decent, and not frivolous.  Also, they share the quality of being Catholic.

Mr. Borgnine's goal of obtaining domestic bliss is occasionally threatened.  His mother complains about the chemistry teacher, because of the fact that she is not Italian.  Also, Mr. Borgnine almost blows it by insisting that the woman kiss him on his first date.  Also, during the course of his first date, Mr. Borgnine's date is interrupted by his friends (in an automobile) who invite him to spend and evening with a slut in the back seat.  Also, Mr. Borgnine, in the course of his first date, is in danger of blowing it because of his behavior in conducting the date as a monologue (basically, his modus operandi in conducting the date is to narrate his own biography).  Another stress point, is that Mr. Borgnine's friends refer to the woman (the first date) as a "dog," meaning that she is ugly.  Despite these potential roadblocks, Mr. Borgnine is not derailed from his goals, and he remains admirably focuesed on his goal of winning the reward of domestic bliss.  Although the film does not conclude with any marriage ceremony, it is apparent by the end of the film, that Mr. Borgnine has captured the heart of the chemistry teacher.

BETSY BLAIR.  Actress and dancer Betsy Blair provides the love interest.  In MARTY, she is reticent in speaking, and is a decided introvert.  But these work to Mr. Borgnine's advantage, because he has the same qualities which, in a similarly encumbered counterpart, can ignite the chemistry of love.  At any rate, it is interesting to know that Betsy Blair was married (in real life) to none other than Gene Kelly, one of the most beloved and adored actors in the history of Hollywood.  Another interesting fact, is that Betsy Blair almost got turned down for the part because she was being investigated by HUAC for alleged sympathy with the Communist party.

CONCLUSION.  MARTY does not have any particular plot.  It is the case, instead, that MARTY documents one of a dozen or so typical life pathways of a mid-thirties man, in his quest for domestic bliss.  In this case, Mr. Borgnine's quest is to find a wife, and also, to rise above his role of being an ordinary butcher, and to own his own butcher shop.  The movie provides a skillful account of the "drama queen" personality.  In this movie, there are three drama queens: Husband, husband's mother, and wife.  The three of them are exceptionally skilled at getting into arguments with each other.  Similar "drama queen" type bickering can be found in ABOUT SCHMIDT, with Jack Nicholson, and in the film, AMADEUS.  A continual theme in MARTY, which adds charm to the movie, are the Italianisms, which take the form of broken English, pride for Italian things (Mr. Borgnine expressed pride in Italian meat for his butcher shop), and Sunday mass.

The film is also to be commended for its total absence of violence, absence of guns, absence of bad language, and absence of computer graphics. An excellent counterpoint to MARTY is the film, REQUIEM FOR A HEAVYWEIGHT, starring Anthony Quinn.  This movie also concerns a man who occupies a challenging transition point in his career,and who also has had bad luck with women.  But in REQUIEM, it is the case that Anthony Quinn is at the verge of success with finding a mate, but his blows it, and he loses the woman.  Thus, I think it might be a good idea to watch MARTY and also REQUIEM at the same sitting.  Unlike MARTY, REQUIEM is a very unusual movie, with intriguingly unique characters, for example, a female gangster named, "Ma Greenie."  FOUR STARS.
